<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-09-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-09-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="220" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d220">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72112/181</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-09-29">
                                    <hi rend="italic">September 29, 1914</hi>.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: I prepared this
                                instruction<note n="7" xml:id="d220fn1">No enclosure with file copy
                                of this letter.</note> with the idea that it be sent at once so that
                            it could be in Ambassador Page’s hands in case his informal
                            representations failed. My idea was to avoid any criticism of the
                            Administration for failure to protest promptly against infringement of
                            American rights. The President, however, thought it would be better to
                            await the result of the telegraphic instruction of last night<note n="8" xml:id="d220fn2">
                                <ref target="frus1914Supp#pg_232">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1914, supp., p.
                                    232</ref>.</note> which was based on the annexed.<note n="7" xml:id="d220fn3">No enclosure with file copy of this letter.</note>
                        </p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>